<h2>
Research <span>Overview</span>
</h2>

<p>
Alternative splicing is a central mechanism of transcriptomic regulation. By selectively including or excluding exons and splice sites, cells can generate multiple RNA transcripts from a single gene, expanding functional diversity without changing the underlying DNA sequence.
</p>

<p>
At PanorOmics, alternative splicing is presented as a major transcriptomic research area: a regulatory layer connecting RNA processing, gene expression, isoform biology, cancer mechanisms, neurological disease, therapeutic discovery, and multi-omics interpretation.
</p>

